              "origin": "syntopicon",
              "content": "<p> Taken literally, the Era of Wrath and Wickedness stretched from 516 BCE beyond the destruction of the Second Temple in 70 CE and the final ruin of Judaism and the Early Church in Palestine in 135 CE at the hads of the pagan Romans. Indeed, it extended until the advent of the Prophet Muḥammad’s mission in 610 CE. It was, of course, during this Time of Wickedness that the powerful and wealthy among the Children of Israel would reject the Messiah Jesus Christ, who had brought them potential respite and renewal if they followed him, and they would attempt to crucify him, only increasing God’s wrath upon them all. After his coming, the Prophet Muḥammad’s mission in this world lasted twenty-three lunar years or twenty-two solar years, from thirteen years before his migration to Medina (<em>al-Hijra</em>) in<em> </em>610 CE, which is the first year of the Muslim lunar calendar, until the Prophet’s passing in 11/632 CE. Muslims refer to these pivotal years of universal and cosmic salvation history as the Age of Supreme Happiness (<em>‘Aṣr al-Sa‘āda</em>). From the standpoint of the Keepers of the Dead Sea Scroll, this Age of Supreme Happiness brought an end to the Age of Wrath and Wickedness and ushered in a Golden Age. </p><p>     The Prophet Muḥammad was born on April 22, 571 CE. It is said that the darkness is thickest just before the break of dawn. Interestingly, only thirty-five years before the Prophet’ birth--which was the dawn of a new age after the long Era of Wrath and Wickednss, the earth experienced one of the darkest and most difficult years of its known geological history, marking, no doubt, the closing stages of the Age of Wrath and Wickedness. This was the fateful year of 536 CE, which some modern historians have called it “the worst year to have ever been alive.” To many contemporaries, the devastating year of 536 CE rightfull seemed like the end of the world, since it was one of the Signs of the End of Time. From the time of Adam until the sounding of the Trumpet, the entire script of human history plays itself out under overarching portents of the Signs of the End of Time, which are often darkly ominous but occasionally startlingly brilliant in their light. The year 536 CE was among the dark of Portents of the End of the World, but it was also a herald of the advent of one of the most luminous of those Signs, which would be the birth of the Prophet Muḥammad, just thirty-five years later. His birth announced the beginning of a new time, and his Prophetic mission--forty years later--which would usher in the Golden Age and finally bring an end to more than a millennium of the Age of Wrath and Wickedness. During the entire year of 536 CE, extreme darkness and cold covered the earth. Apparently, this cataclysm was linked with massive volcanic eruptions in Iceland and the Americas, which apparently began in the spring of 536 CE, clouding the skies with ash and possibly also bringing about a series of mysterious fogs that year which are reported in historical annals. Some regions reported deathly twenty-four-hour periods of darkness that lasted for as much as one year and a half (eighteen months). In some regions, summer temperatures hovered just above freezing between 35 to 37 degrees Fahrenheit (1.5 to 2.5 degrees Centigrade), and there were reports of summer snowfalls in China. Irish chronicles of the period report a failure of bread from the years 536 until 539 CE. Naturally, in the absences of the sun’s life-giving rays, crops failed everywhere and the normal patterns of the environment and agriculture were upset. In 541 CE, the Bubonic plague--which came to be known as “Justinian’s Plauge,” since he was the Roman emperor at the time--broke out in certain parts of the Byzantine Empire and spread rapidly elsewhere, wiping out as much as one third of the population of the Eastern Roman Empire. The Byzantine historian Procopius writes that when the sun did rarely shine during that year--“it gave forth its light without brightness like the moon.” In the Roman Empire, China, the Middle East, parts of Eurasia, South America, and elsewhere, tens of millions of human beings lost their lives during this Little Ice Age of Late Antiquity. The ensuing decade after 536 CE was one of the coldest in thousands of years of previous geological history, and the harmful after-effects of this year of constant darkness, perpetual winter, unusual cold, starvation, and plague lasted for another decade until roughly twenty-five years before the Prophet’s birth. Parts of Northern Europe felt the injurious effects of the decade beginning in 536 CE and its aftermath well into beginning years of the period of the Rightly Guided Caliphate, which began in the year 11/632 CE. </p>",
