              "origin": "syntopicon",
              "content": "<p><strong> Banū Khazraj </strong>or simply Khazraj was the largest Arabian tribe in pre-Islamic Yathrib and the city of Medina during the era of the Prophet. Like their cousins Banū Aws, Khazraj were pure Arabians (<em>al-‘Arab al-‘Āriba</em>), descending from Qaḥṭān and not from Abraham and the Arabized Arabs (<em>al-‘Arab al-Musta‘riba</em>) through his descendent ‘Adnān. Again, like their cousins, Banū Khazraj were forced to leave their Southern homeland sometime probably around 300 CE after the rupture of the Great Dam of Mar’ib, if not before that time. One Arabic history asserts that they and Aws had settled in Yathrib roughly during the second century CE. Together with Aws, Banū Khazraj was known in pre-Islamic Arabia as Banū Qayla (the Children of Qayla). All sources concur, however, that Banū Khazraj and Banū Aws became bitter rivals in Yathrib, which ultimately led to Civil War in the Oasis. The Civil War then culminated in 617 CE in the Battle of Bu‘āth, only five years prior to the Prophet’s Migration (<em>Hijra</em>) to Medina in the year 1/622. In that battle, Banū Khazraj fought alongside their Jewish allies, Banū al-Naḍīr and Banū Qurayẓa. Banū Aws, on the other hand, had the assistance of their ally, Banū Qaynuqā‘, which was the most powerful of the Jewish tribes of Medina. After a desperate battle, Banū Aws--who had virtually been routed--miraculously turned the tide of the battle and inflicted a great defeat upon Banū Khazraj and their allies. The chieftain of Banū Khazraj was ‘Abd-Allāh ibn Ubayy ibn Salūl, who was also the leader of the party of the Hypocrites (<em>al-Munāfiqūn</em>), who continually plotted against the Prophet. The tribe of Banū Khazraj, however, was strong in its belief and fidelity toward the Prophet and was not guilty--as a whole--of the hypocrisy of its chieftain.  </p>",
              "sectionId": "book-five-god-s-last-messenger-muhammad-best-known-most-closely-observed-most-successful-of-all-god-s-prophets"
